<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris Court Rejects Case on World Cup Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A Paris court on Friday rejected a
case brought by some European Parliament members demanding the
redistribution of more than 700,000 World Cup tickets to give
foreign fans a fairer chance.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal of Grand Instance of Paris said it could not rule
in the case because the deputies had themselves not tried to buy
tickets and therefore were unable to take legal action in the
interests of others or the general public.
</P>
<P>
Thirty European Parliament deputies sued the World Cup
organizers on charges of unfairly organizing ticket sales on May
20. The court had deferred its ruling until Friday.
</P>
<P>
The deputies said 2.5 million tickets distributed by the French
Committee of Organization of World Cup (CFO), the International
Federation of Football (FIFA) and the French Federation of
Football (FFF) were discriminatory because most of them were
reserved for French fans.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers, who are from Belgium, Britain, the Netherlands,
Germany, Greece, Austria, Italy and Denmark, demanded that the
712,484 tickets be redistributed to anyone who wished to watch the
matches, whatever his or her nationality.
</P>
<P>
But lawyers for the FFF, FIFA and CFO said tickets already sold
could not be redistributed and the sales had not violated European
Union rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
