<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Rejects Liberalization of Law on Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Friday rejected the idea to liberalize France's law on crackdown
of drug trafficking and abuse which has been maintained since
1970.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting consecrated to the fight against drugs, Chirac
said that all 15 member states of the European Union (EU), except
the Netherlands, have similar laws against drug crimes.
</P>
<P>
"We should not liberalize that. Each time I met some
professionals, this idea reinforced. There is no prevention
without education. Moreover, there is no prevention without
banning," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also regretted that within EU the concertation is never
strong enough for an efficient common policy against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Some leftwing French politicians have suggested a loosening of
France's law on drugs, which they regard as too strict against
drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that the government should adopt a policy which is
both "humane and efficient" to treat drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
In France, a convicted drug addict should be imposed heavy
fines or given tough jail sentences.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
