<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Remains at 28-year Low in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate held
at a 28-year low of 4.3 percent in May as the robust economic
growth produced nearly 300,000 new jobs, offsetting fallout from
Asia's economic crisis, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted rate matched that of April and was the
lowest since February 1970.
</P>
<P>
Employers added 296,000 jobs to their payrolls in May, nearly
matching the gain of 302,000 in April, which was revised up from
an early estimate of 262,000.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the stronger-than-expected report, which also
showed healthy wage gains, raised the prospect that the Federal
Reserve might raise interest rates later this year to slow
economic growth and thus nip any acceleration in inflation.
</P>
<P>
Job gains were strongest in services and retail sales. However,
manufacturers cut 26,000 positions and during the previous three
months had added only 2,000 jobs, which are regarded as related to
the Asian economic problems. From March 1996 to January 1998,
manufacturers added 370,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Some of the biggest losses in manufacturing came in the apparel
industry, down 9,000, and electronic equipment, industrial
machinery and autos.
</P>
<P>
Construction payrolls declined 9,000 in May, marking at least a
pause in what's been strong growth since last fall. Mining jobs
fell by 13,000.
</P>
<P>
Job growth was strong at temporary help firms, in data
processing and computers and in finance. Retail establishments
added 89,000 jobs, with especially robust growth occurring at
restaurants, department stores, drug stores and gift shops.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that strong demand for labor is
showing up in Americans' paycheck. Average hourly earnings rose 4
cents in May to 12.73 U.S. dollars after advancing 6 cents in April. The
average is 4.3 percent higher than a year ago, a substantial
amount considering inflation is hovering under 2 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
