<HEADLINE> Paris Inaugurates Square in Memory of World Cup Founder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of Paris
Friday inaugurated a square in memory of the founder of the
football World Cup, Frenchman Jules Rimet, just four days from the
opening of the football finals.
</P>
<P>
The square is located near the Parc des Princes stadium of
Paris, which is one of the 10 stadiums across France to host the
matches.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was presided over by Paris Mayor Jean Tiberi and
attended by the great-daughter of Rimet, president of the
International Football Federation (FIFA) Joao Havelange, and the
president of Rimet Association Jean-Yves Guillain.
</P>
<P>
Rimet founded football World Cup in 1928, whose first matches
were held in 1930 in Uruguay. He also founded the League of
Football Association in 1910 to promote professionalism in sports.
</P>
<P>
Rimet, who was president of the French Football Federation from
1945 to 1949, died in 1956.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
