<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Strokes Rise in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- After many years of decline, the
number of strokes in Canada has been accelerating sharply in the
past decade, says a study.
</P>
<P>
About 48,000 Canadians had strokes last year, and at least
6,000 were fatal. About 65 percent of the survivors were left with
paralysis, loss of speech or mental impairment, according to the
study released Thursday by the Heart and Stroke Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Within 10 years, the number of strokes in Canada could rise to
more than 60,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
As the population keeps aging, the totals could keep rising to
close to 80,000 a years within two decades.
</P>
<P>
"Only a small percentage of people are getting the message and
many of them tend to forget it," said Dr. Frank Silver, an Ottawa
neurologist on the board of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
A survey found that only 39 percent of Canadians can identify
even one of the symptoms of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
Another study found that only about half of the people would
seek immediate medical attention if they had one of the
symptoms: sudden dizziness, severe headache, weakness on one side
or inability to speak.
</P>
<P>
Unless the large number of people heading into their 50s and
60s start taking preventive action and learn to recognize warning
signs, strokes and disabilities caused by them are expected to
increase dramatically in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
