<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bill Sets Terms for Release of N. Irish Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The British government published a
bill on Friday which sets terms on releasing Northern Irish
guerrilla prisoners in line with the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Faced with anger among mainstream pro-British Protestants over
the release promise, Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam promised
there would be no "general amnesty" to the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
"The gates of the Maze Prison will not suddenly be thrown
open," she said in a statement, calming the fears of the
Protestants who account for 60 percent of the local population in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace deal that was endorsed in a referendum last
month, several hundred prisoners held in Northern Ireland's Maze
prison, members either of Republican or pro-British Loyalist
groups, could be released in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
But the new Northern Ireland (Sentences) Bill can bar early
release of prisoners of some guerrilla groups which are counted as
"terrorist organizations."
</P>
<P>
A "terrorist organization" is defined as one which "is
concerned in terrorism connected with the affairs of Northern
Ireland, or in promoting or encouraging it, and which has not
established or is not maintaining a complete and unequivocal
ceasefire".
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said the bill included "rigorous safeguards" which would
ensure that only prisoners who had genuinely given up violence
would be released.
</P>
<P>
An independent body will be set up to review the individual
applications from prisoners from organizations qualifying for the
release program.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, all those set free ahead of time will be out on
license and can be locked up again on the order of the government
if they are considered likely to breach the terms of their
release.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
