<HEADLINE> U.S. Automakers Support China MFN Renewal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Automakers in the United States
are demanding that U.S. Congress renew the most favored nation
status to China as it is in the U.S. interest.
</P>
<P>
In a statement received here Friday, President of the American
Automobile Manufacturers Association (AAMA) Andrew H. Card, Jr.
said U.S. car makers strongly support continuing normal trade
relations with China through the renewal of its MFN status.
</P>
<P>
"In the year since the last MFN debate, economic and strategic
crises throughout Asia have created new and serious instability in
the region. Denying MFN to China today would make solutions to
these challenges more difficult to achieve," the President said.
</P>
<P>
"Changing course would serve no U.S. interest," he added.
</P>
<P>
"There has never been a more important time for the U.S. to
continue to strengthen its trading relationship with the world's
most populous country. Congress should act swiftly and
unequivocally to reaffirm longstanding U.S. policy of normal
trade ties with China," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
