<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Nunavut Faces a Tough Road Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's new territory of Nunavut,
which is to come into being next April, will face a series of
social and economic problems and a tough task ahead.
</P>
<P>
The territory, hived off from the northern Northwest Territory,
will cover one quarter of Canada's land mass, and a population of
25,000.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it is destined to have the most dire social and economic
conditions in the country, all compounded by the region's harsh
climate and isolated communities, according to the Globe and Mail
newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
At present, one third of its residents survive on welfare, and
rates of suicide, teen-age pregnancy and substance abuse soar
above the national averages.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita income is estimated at about 7,600 U.S. dollars, and
the living costs there is over 160 percent higher than the
national average.
</P>
<P>
Canada's federal government is widely said to be ready to
provide about 400 million U.S. dollars a year for the new
jurisdiction. But that is considered to be only what is needed to
maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
With a much younger population and almost no industries, the
new Inuit government will be hard pressed to provide adequate
jobs, housing and medical services.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the bleak future ahead, Inuit leaders and federal
officials suggest that a government closer to the people in
Nunavut will stand a better chance of solving the problems there.
</P>
<P>
"The federal and territorial governments have been a real part
of the problem," Jose Kusugak, head of an organization
representing Inuit living in the new territory, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"When you have a totally different race of people running your
lives, it can create a terrible feeling of uselessness," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Vows to Keep Offshore Sector Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has vowed to safeguard its
offshore sector in negotiations with the European Union (EU) on
its membership.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said here Friday
the sector is so important for Cyprus that the government puts it
on the top of the priority list of issues to be negotiated with
the EU.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the one-day conference on the prospect of
country's offshore sector, or the service industry for foreign
companies in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus started accession negotiations with the EU last
March. And it is widely expected that the EU will ask Cyprus to
adjust the island's preferential policies to foreign companies so
as to meet the organization's criteria.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, lack of natural resources, started its offshore sector
in 1975, which is now at a developed stage featured by
well-educated labor force, good infrastructure and various
supporting systems.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou singled out the preferential tax regime -- as low
as 4 percent -- and the agreements of avoiding double-taxation
with a number of countries as key factors contributing to the
success of the offshore sector.
</P>
<P>
The sector also benefits the country's employment, transfer of
know-how and tourism, Christodoulou pointed out.
</P>
<P>
About 1,100 offshore enterprises currently have offices on the
island, employing 2,100 Cypriots, or about 1.5 percent of the
island's labour force, and 3,000 expatriates.
</P>
<P>
The sector brought the country some 360 million U.S. dollars in
foreign exchange in 1997, about 4.5 percent of the country's Gross
National Product.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the concern expressed regarding the sector's
future after Cyprus' EU accession, Christodolou told the
conference that the maintenance of the existing offshore regime
"will be a top priority in the contest of the accession
negotiations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
