<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Output Cuts Deal Fails to Impress London Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The London oil market Friday was
little impressed by a surprise agreement among three major world
oil exporters to cut their crude output by 450,000 barrels per day
(bpd) from the over-supplied world markets.
</P>
<P>
World benchmark Brent blend crude oil was not much inspired by
the deal and was trading only 21 cents higher at 14.64 US dollars
per barrel by late afternoon, which is still 5 dollars below last
year's prices.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the new deal between Saudi Arabia,
Venezuela and Mexico was reached in Amsterdam after secret talks
and it followed the cuts of 1.5 million bpd agreed under a
landmark pact in March in the Saudi capital Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the new cuts were still not enough to bring
oil prices back to a decent level of 16-18 dollars a barrel, and
many believe around a million barrels a day needs to be cut from
drenched Western markets.
</P>
<P>
"Now the hard work begins. It's a step in the right direction
but they now need to get cooperation from the other producers,"
said one dealer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there is deep scepticism about promised oil output
cuts among oil traders as they are very familiar with broken
promises.
</P>
<P>
They estimate that less than a million of the promised Riyadh
cuts of 1.5 million were actually made and see the additional
Amsterdam reductions merely as a patch-up for the original
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"If the original cutbacks had taken place then prices would
gradually be recovering by now," said another dealer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
