<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Statement on Greco-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has welcomed as "a positive
event" a NATO statement Thursday that Greece and Turkey intend to
implement earlier agreements recognizing each other's sovereignty
and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his press briefing Friday, Government Spokesman
Christos Stylianides said "any move to ease tensions in the Aegean
creates a positive climate for developments in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana issued a statement
Thursday in Brussels that Greece and Turkey intend to implement
fully the agreements reached in 1988 under which they respect the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of each other and their
rights to use the high seas and international air space of the
Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Solana said the statement is "a manifestation of the political
will of the two governments to continue to respect these
principles and to carry out in good faith the range of confidence
building measures that have been agreed."
</P>
<P>
Stylianides, however, said that the Cyprus question is not
linked to this agreement.
</P>
<P>
Greece, an ally of Cyprus, and Turkey have been at odds on a
number of issues, especially the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
