<HEADLINE> Greece to Try to Make More Specific Solana's Announcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos said Friday that Greece would do its utmost to make even
more specific the announcement by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) Secretary-General Javier Solana on the
confidence-building measures (CBMS) in the Aegean Sea region.
</P>
<P>
Solana announced in Brussels Thursday that both Greece and
Turkey had agreed to a series of CBMS which were based on two
memoranda of understanding reached by the two countries in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at press conference, Pangalos regarded Solana's
announcement as "quite general". He also admitted that the
announcement contained a number of new elements.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos also said that the
announcement voiced the "common political will" of Greece and Turkey
to implement the 1998 agreement, but certain arrangements required
further elaboration as a supplement or prerequisite for its
realization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas described
the announcement as "a positive step" which however did not go far
enough.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it must be implemented in practice, with
respect for the national integrity and independence of each country.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds over decades for their
differences in the territorial waters, air space limits, the
delimitation of continental shelf in the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1988 agreements signed by the then foreign
ministers of Greece's Karolos Papoulias and Turkey's Mesut Yilmaz,
the two neighboring countries agreed to respect each other's
sovereignty and territorial integrity, and their rights to use the
high seas and international air space of the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
The agreements also urged both countries to halt military
exercises in the Aegean during the months of July and August - the
high season for tourism.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey hold regular military exercises in the Aegean,
where they have come close to war in 1996 due to Turkey's claims
to the Greek uninhabited islands.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has since Wednesday began a sea and air exercise in the
Aegean. 30 Turkish war planes reportedly violated flight regulations
in the Athens Flight Information Region and were intercepted by 20
Greek jet fighters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
