<HEADLINE> Clinton Urged to Withhold Loans to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A key U.S. House member has
urged President Bill Clinton to withhold further International
Monetary Fund (IMF) loans to Russia, accusing Moscow of having
close ties with Iran and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Representative Benjamin Gilman, who chairs
the House International Relations Committee, in a letter to
Clinton dated May 28 but released Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. president, I strongly urge the United States withhold its
support for any additional IMF loans to the government of the
Russian Federation until the concerns I have outlined are
addressed," said Gilman in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Gilman noted that additional IMF lending should be held back
because "I and other members of Congress have been increasingly
disappointed by the conduct of Russian foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
"Russian foreign policy apparently seeks to challenge American
leadership around the world and dissipate America's ability to
organize international cooperation to address pressing problems,"
Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
"This unconstructive approach to our bilateral relationship
comes at a time when the United States must lead the charge on
tremendously serious problems involving proliferation of weapons
of mass destruction and the stabilization and prevention of
conflicts around the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
Later this month , the IMF will provide Russia a loan of 670
million U.S. dollar tranche of an existing 9.2 billion U.S.
dollars. Washington said earlier this week that it would support
additional IMF lending to Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
