<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Exchange Accusations over Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia and Eritrea, which
have been involved in a border dispute, Friday exchanged
accusations of being bombed by the other shortly after an urgent
call by African countries for restraint.
</P>
<P>
A press release faxed here by the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry
claimed that Eritrea carried out an air attack earlier Friday on
Mekelle in northern Ethiopia, wounding five civilians.
</P>
<P>
"While this is, as already indicated, a further escalation of
the war of aggression, it should come as no surprise because by
now it should be clear that the irrationality in Asmara has no
limits," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Ethiopia has in self defense taken limited
measures against Asmara air force base.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Foreign Ministry of Eritrea
confirmed the air bombing by Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
It said two Ethiopian fighter planes bombed the southern
outskirts of Asmara, capital of Eritrea, at 14:00 local time.
</P>
<P>
Half an hour later, another two Ethiopian fighter planes
dropped more bombs in the same locality, it added.
</P>
<P>
The damage to "property or persons" by the attack, which
Eritrea claimed is in line with Ethiopia's "persistent attempts
to escalate the current border dispute", is not immediately
available, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The intensifying situation between the two countries has
aroused grave concern from African countries while leaders of
member states of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) are to
gather here to plan the future of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers from the central organ of the OAU
Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution, at
an urgent session Thursday night, urged both parties to exercise
restraint so as to enable a peaceful settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, who are here to attend the on-going 68th
ordinary session of the OAU Council of Ministers, also urged the
two parties to accept a solution that comes through peaceful
means, including adjudication, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
After about four hours of deliberation, the ministers decided
to remain actively seized of the issue.
</P>
<P>
An OAU source told Xinhua that the ministers would hold
another urgent meeting Friday night to discuss the high tension
triggered off by the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
The three-day council of ministers session, to be closed
Saturday, is to make preparations for the coming OAU summit
starting next Monday.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful solution to the crisis between Ethiopia and Eritrea
is expected to come out at the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
