<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Computer-Literated Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
Friday that all the American students should be computer-literate
before they reach high school and all children should share in
high-tech opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"All students should feel as comfortable with a keyboard as a
chalkboard, as comfortable with a laptop as a textbook," the
president told 2,400 graduates at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
"It is critical to insuring that they all have opportunity in
the world of the 21st century," said Clinton who was campaigning
for his goal of wiring all classrooms to the Internet by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't let a child graduate from middle school anymore
without knowing how to use new technologies to learn," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Ten states already have such a requirement for high school
graduation, but Clinton said the same standard should be applied
for younger children.
</P>
<P>
The president proposed to provide each middle school with
20,000 U.S. dollar federal assistance over three years to promote
high-tech literacy. That means the federal government will budget
180 million dollars for the program between fiscal 2000 and fiscal
2002.
</P>
<P>
Clinton targeted that more than half of the nation's classrooms
will be linked with the Internet within a year. And as a
promotion, he urged telecommunications companies to continue
providing favorable services to poor schools, libraries and rural
health centers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton acknowledged that there is a gap between rich and poor
children in technology opportunities in the United States. But he
said every child in America deserves a chance to participate in
the information revolution.
</P>
<P>
He said affluent schools are nearly three times as likely as
poorer schools to have Internet access in the classroom and white
students are more than twice as likely as blacks to have computers
in their homes.
</P>
<P>
"Unequal education hardens into unequal prospects," Clinton
said, urging private companies to invest in a school, embrace a
community in need, and endow an eager young mind with opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
