<HEADLINE> Nigerian Minister Held Hostage by Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi
was held hostage for three and half hours in the ministry's
office in Abuja Friday, by angry staff who demanded improved
welfare.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said the demonstrating staff locked the
gates of the ministry at about 12:00 in the noon, preventing
anyone from going out.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State in the ministry, Buhari Bala and the
Minister of State for Health, Iyorwuese Hagher, were also caught
in the web.
</P>
<P>
It was only at about 3:20 p.m. that the gates were opened at
the arrival of a detachment of policemen, when the minister of
state for health was seen left in his car.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the workers who identified himself as Henry
said they resorted to the action after entreaties to the minister
to review workers' welfare failed to yield results.
</P>
<P>
The workers complained that top officials of the ministry are
insensitive to the suffering of junior staff.
</P>
<P>
They alleged that they were not paid their relocation
allowance when the ministry was relocated from Lagos to Abuja.
They also complained that all the staff buses had broken down.
</P>
<P>
The allegations were, however, denied by Jubrin Chinade, the
ministry's Perminent Secretary, when he spoke to journalists
after the gates were opened.
</P>
<P>
Chinade insisted that the ministry is giving top priority to
the welfare of its staff. In fact, he said, the Foreign Ministry
provides better welfare to its workers than any other ministries.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the ministry has over 1,300 houses for
its staff and "no other ministry has that much."
</P>
<P>
"The ministry of Foreign Affairs is the only ministry where
drivers have two bedroom flat for accommodation. We have the
largest fleet of vehicles that convey staffers to and from work,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On the relocation allowance, he said, the package was for
ministries that moved to Abuja in 1996, while the foreign
ministry, which moved to Abuja in 1990, was not effected by the
package.  
</P>
