intended protest action this week because of the retrenchment policies
said they would go ahead unless discussions with the state on Monday
produced something more concrete.
</P>
<P>
The unions were briefed Friday on the Education Department's
tentative proposals, including the possible withdrawal of the
right-sizing plans published by the department in April, should the
unions suggest workable alternatives.
</P>
<P>
The department also offered to extend contracts of temporary
teachers for six months until December, and to consider an average
pupil/teacher ratio of 34:1.
</P>
<P>
The National Professional Teachers Organization (Naptosa),
representing 66,000 members, on Friday officially gave notice of their
intended strike next Friday, saying the tentative proposals by the
state could at this stage not be accepted.
</P>
<P>
The Suid-Afrikaanse Onderwysersunie (SAOU), who gave notice
Thursday that its 34,000 mainly Afrikaans speaking teachers would
go on strike in two weeks' time, said while slight progress was
made, it was still not satisfying.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging the ministry's attempt to defuse the explosive
situation, the unions said they were continuing with the planning of
the protests.
</P>
<P>
They said they remained open to negotiations and urged the ministry
to solve the fundamental problem of the underfunding of education.
</P>
<P>
The South African Democratic Teachers' Union (Sadtu),
representing 170,000 teachers, last week indicated it would start
protest Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three unions together represent more than 77 percent of the
country's 350,000 teachers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
