<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Suffers from Minor Illness, his </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei only feels unwell and there is no cause for concern, his
office announced Saturday in a statement carried by state-run
Tehran radio.
</P>
<P>
Head of Khamenei's office Mohammad Golpaygani said in the
statement that Khamenei is only facing "minor problems."
</P>
<P>
The statement confirmed that Khamenei has been ill since
Thursday when he made an unusual short speech in a low tune to
mark the ninth anniversary of the demise of the late Iranian
supreme leader Ayatollah Khomeini. However, it revealed no details
about Khamenei's illness.
</P>
<P>
The health condition of the Iranian supreme leader has raised
concerns at home and abroad, the Iranian Tehran Times daily
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An informed source told the daily on Friday that people from
across the country and even abroad have been calling the leader's
office these days, inquiring about Khamenei's health condition.
</P>
<P>
The calls were sparked by the unusually short speech of less
than 15 minutes made by Khamenei Thursday at the ceremony marking
the anniversary of Khomeini's death.
</P>
<P>
"My friends and doctors would not allow me to talk longer than
this," Khamenei told his guests at Khomeini's mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
On May 30, he showed the sign of an unusual health condition
when he made a speech in a low and uneasy tone during a meeting
with the members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei, 59, succeeded the most powerful position in Iran
hours after Khomeini's death on June 4, 1989. He is believed to be
one of the best orators and sermonizers in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
