<HEADLINE> Thai Minister Denies Banknote-Printing Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda has denied press reports that his country would
print more money to deal with the money crunch in the country.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said earlier that Tarrin, during his recent visit
to Japan, pledged to print more banknotes.
</P>
<P>
However, he was quoted Saturday by the newspaper Bangkok Post
as saying some people may have misinterpreted remarks he had made
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said that while in Japan he was only talking about the
extension of the monetary base through the restructuring of the
credit system or injection by the Bank of Thailand of liquidity
into productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
"This was not new. It was included in Thailand's fourth letter
of intent submitted to the IMF," Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible for us to allow a policy of printing
banknotes. We fear inflation and lack of fiscal and monetary
discipline," he said.
</P>
<P>
If Thailand printed more bills and injected them into the
system, that would mean that the country really lacked fiscal and
monetary discipline and this would affect the country's
reliability, Tarrin noted.
</P>
<P>
Some international organizations have urged Thailand to
increase the money supply in the market to stimulate the economy,
according to Finance Ministry officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
