<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kuanda's Political Withdrawal Widely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian President Kenneth
Kaunda's announcement to quit party politics has been welcomed by
the government and opposition parties but evoked mixed feelings
in his opposition United National Independence Party (UNIP).
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held in Lusaka Thursday, Kaunda announced
that he was strongly considering the possibility of detaching
himself from party politics and will not offer himself for
re-election at UNIP's forthcoming extraordinary congress which he
recommanded to hold later this year.
</P>
<P>
The 74-year old former president said he made the decision to
help the countries opposition parties become stronger and making
contribution to the nation "on a wider scope".
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made three days after Kuanda, who had
been detained for over five months and charged with misprison of
treason for allegedly concealing knowledge of last October's
foiled military coup, was released by the Lusaka High Court since
the state entered a nolle prosequi against him.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's announcement to quit party politics was widely
welcomed by the Zambian government and the country's other
opposition parties and organizations including Zambia Democratic
Congress (ZDC), Grassroots Welfare Party, Zambia Democratic Party
and Zambia independent monitoring team.
</P>
<P>
Legal Affairs Minister Vincent Malambo said at a news briefing
here Thursday that the move taken by Kuanda to consider stepping
down from politics is welcome and it is going to earn him the
respect that he deserves.
</P>
<P>
While Dean Mung'omba,the Zambia Democratic Congress president
who has been arrested and charged with treason in connection with
last year's military coup, also said Thursday that he welcomed
Kaunda's decision to resign form politics while stressing
Kaunda's experience in politics is needed by all political
parties on order to survive.
</P>
<P>
Besides the political forces, Times of Zambia, the country's
biggest daily paper, also appreciated Kaunda's decision to resign
and said that he has played his part and in a great way too, but
"every game has to be played within certain limits of time."
</P>
<P>
In a editorial published Saturday, the paper also pointed out
that if Kuanda, who led Zambia to independence in 1964 from
Britain and ruled the country for 27 years, had resigned in 1991
after he was defeated by President Frederick Chiluba in the
year's general election, he could have been one of the most
outstanding statesmen Africa has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
However, Kaunda's decision to quit politics and the country's
former ruling UNIP which he founded, has evoked mixed feelings in
the country's largest opposition party.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders and cadres were shocked and tried to digest
the announcement by Kaunda's intention to resign.
</P>
<P>
Some of them in the party, which has been bogged down in a
long-time inter-fighting, said that the Kaunda's exit form UNIP
leadership will spell doom for the party while others said that
Kaunda has betrayed them.
</P>
<P>
Those who don't want Kuanda to step down also said that it will
be difficult for UNIP to find somebody universally acceptable to
take over the leadship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
