<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Fires Striking Union Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) on
Saturday fired all 29 officers of the Airline Pilots Association
of the Philippines (ALPAP) which staged what the authorities
called an illegal strike late Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The airlines declared all the 29 officers of the 620-member PAL
pilots union, including its president, as having lost their
employment status, effective Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The company also gave the other striking union members until
noon Sunday to report back for work, or else face the same fate.
</P>
<P>
Members of the ALPAP went on strike late Friday afternoon to
protest the ordered retirement of a pilot last year, stranding
thousands of passengers at the Manila international and all other
domestic airports in the country.
</P>
<P>
The strike openly defied two orders of the Labor Department to
maintain the status quo and was labeled as "illegal" by Labor
Secretary Cresenciano Trajano Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the labor code, any strike undertaken without the
permission of the labor authorities is illegal and the union
officers and members participating in the strike are deemed to
have lost their jobs for their act.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP members had been threatening to go on strike against
PAL's alleged unfair labor practices and union busting.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Labor Department took over the labor dispute at
PAL and issued two orders mandating the maintenance of the status
quo at the airlines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
