<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Encourages Overseas Investment in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
has announced new policies to encourage overseas investment
in its agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies that invest in agriculture, forestry, animal
husbandry, fishery and related processing industries for a term of
more than 15 years are entitled to preferential policies, one of
which is refund of agriculture tax and duties on special farm
produce for three years after the invested projects begin to
generate profits.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors will also be exempt from income tax for two
years after they begin to make profits, and they will be only pay
50 percent of the normal taxes in the third, fourth and fifth years.
</P>
<P>
Even the locally received taxes collected during the
third-to-fifth years may be refunded with official approval. Fifty
percent of the locally received taxes collected during the
sixth-to-10th years may also be refunded. The income taxes are
composed of parts received by the central government and the local
governments, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Besides the above policies, investors in high-tech agricultural
projects can enjoy tax returns ranging from 15 percent to 30
percent for another five years.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has also extended the term of overseas investors' land
use and enterprise operation right to 30 years, and to as long as
50 years for overseas companies that invest in the development of
barren hills, neglected slopes and beaches, and untapped water and
land resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
