<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Promoting Marine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 6 (Xinhua) -- South China's island province of
Hainan has been successful in developing its marine economy.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that Hainan's marine economy was worth
more than 10 billion yuan last year, a surge of 35 percent from
1996.
</P>
<P>
The growth momentum has continued this year.
</P>
<P>
The marine-based tourism industry of Hainan, which is also
China's largest special economic zone, attracted over five million
domestic and overseas tourists last year, with earnings rocketing
43 percent on a year-by-year basis to 4.73 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Other industries based in offshore waters such as marine
transportation, the raising of aquatic products, salt and undersea
mining have also experienced considerable growth in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 1,000 enterprises specialize in marine
industries, with total assets worth 13.4 billion yuan and a
combined payroll of 60,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has an area of more than two million sq km of offshore
waters, about two-thirds of China's total. The waters are rich in
natural resources, including 40 billion tons of oil, 15 trillion
cubic meters of natural gas and 43 million tons of
ilmenite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
