<HEADLINE> Pak PM Leaves for United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif left here Saturday for a visit to the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) and Saudi Arabia to discuss the situation arising from India
and Pakistan's nuclear tests last month.
</P>
<P>
Talking briefly to reporters before departure, Sharif said he
had sought advice from leaders of the two brotherly Gulf countries
after New Delhi set off five nuclear devices on May 11 and 13.
</P>
<P>
"I will now discuss post-detonations' scenario with these
countries," Sharif said, referring to Pakistan's own six nuclear
tests last week, for which the United States and Japan have
already announced to impose economic sanctions on the country.
</P>
<P>
He called the visit part of regular consultations with the two
countries, which have very strong relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Sharif will meet UAE ruler Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al-Nahayan
before proceeding to Saudi Arabia. He is accompanied by Finance
Minister Sartaj Aziz, Petroleum Minister Chaudhry Nisar Ali Khan
and Punjab Minister Shahbaz Sharif. 
</P>
