<HEADLINE> FIFA Candidate Pledges Top Position For Non-European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- UEFA president Lennart Johansson
promised on Saturday that he will appoint a general secretary from
outside Europe if he is elected Monday president of FIFA, the
world soccer ruling body.
</P>
<P>
Johansson, locked in a presidency campaign with currently FIFA
general secretary Sepp Blatter, made the remarks when he met
supporters and reporters at a reception to mark Sweden's national
day.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old Swede, who has been subject to criticism in
some quarters for being too Euro-centric, made the promise in a
bid to boost his votes from outside Europe in Monday's Congress
vote on a successor to outgoing president Joao Havelange.
</P>
<P>
"Some people in Asia have concerns whether Lennart Johansson is
too European-centred, simply because he is the president of UEFA,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"So his general secretary should come from Africa, Asia,
CONCACAF or CONMEBOL -- the Confederations outside Europe."
</P>
<P>
It have been rumoured that if Johansson does beat Blatter in
Monday's vote at the FIFA Congress, Peter Velappan of Malaysia,
current general secretary of the Asian Football Confederation
(AFC), would get the job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
