<HEADLINE> Karl Malone Displays Badly in NBA Finals Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Karl Malone, NBA's Most Valuable
Player last season, had a bad run for the second straight time in
the NBA Finals, and this time, he wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
"I got away with it in the first game, but today we didn't get
away with it," he said after the Bulls beat the Jazz 93-88 to tie
the best of seven series 1-all last night.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz looked not like themselves at all in the final
quarter, blew a lead entering the period for the first time in 60
games. And now the home-court advantage has reverted to Chicago in
the next three games.
</P>
<P>
Malone again had a low score, finishing with 16 points on
5-for-16 shooting. Though he grabbed 12 rebounds, yet Dennis
Rodman surpassed him in this field by landing nine in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
"We will not win this series if I don't play better," Malone
said. "But I think the worst thing in the world for me to do now
is try to put the whole weight of the team on my shoulders."
</P>
<P>
Malone was not the only member of the team who had a poor
showing under the pressure last night. The whole team almost
collapsed in the fourth quarter, failing to score anything during
six attacks, while the Bulls converted Utah's 20 turnovers into 30
points during the game.
</P>
<P>
"We just tried to take point guards Howard Eisley and John
Stockton out of the flow," Chicago coach Phil Jackson said of the
Bulls' fourth-quarter strategy. "We thought we could disrupt their
offense."
</P>
<P>
That worked pretty well. The Jazz only got one point in their
first 10 possessions for the fourth quarter. After teaming for 18
points and 13 assists in the first three quarters, Eisley and
Stockton had just one assist and no point between them in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
"We definitely have the confidence to come back," Antoine Carr
said. "We have to compete better than we did tonight."
</P>
<P>
Game 3 will start Sunday in Chicago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
