<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Tiger Gives Birth Through Caesarian Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A 14-year-old South China tiger has
given birth to three cubs after undergoing a Caesarian operation.
</P>
<P>
The tiger, named Xionghuan, was reared in the Xiongsen Bear and
Tiger Village in Guilin, in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
As Xionghuan was suffering difficult labor after 105 days of
pregnancy, veterinarians in the Village performed a Caesarian
operation, the first of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
The three cubs first suffered from hypoxia and coma, and the
veterinarians hurriedly took emergency measures, such as
oxygen therapy, massotherapy and artificial respiration.
</P>
<P>
One cub died, but the other two survived.
</P>
<P>
The South China tiger, a rare species, has a life span of 18 to
20 years. There are fewer than 30 left in the world, including
eight in the Guilin Xiongsen Bear and Tiger Village. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0086 </DOCNO>
