<HEADLINE> Vietnam Spells out new Policy for Border Trade With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- All businesses headquartered in a
border gate area with China will be permitted to directly import
and export all kinds of commodities from June 20, official reports
here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This is a decision made by Vietnam's prime minister on
experimental application of several policies in Mong Cai border
gate's area in the northern province of Quang Ninh.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision on June 4, imports and exports of
commodities controled by quotas will be carried out in accordance
with the state's currently effective regulations and the ministry
of trade's instructions.
</P>
<P>
The decision also wrote policies on tourist services,
investment and infrastructure construction in Mong Cai area.
</P>
<P>
Under the decision, foreign tourists arriving in international
sea ports in Quang Ninh province by ships and under contracts
signed with domestic tourist companies will have their entry-exit
procedures cleared by the relevant authorities right at the ports.
</P>
<P>
They will also be permitted to tour Mong Cai border gate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Customs Seize Huge Quantity of Fake World Cup Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- French customs officials have seized
120,000 footballs, T-shirts, CD-Roms and other products which
violate the copyrights of the logos for World Cup football finals.
</P>
<P>
Most of these products came from Asia and were aimed at
European markets, said officials, who are destroying the fake
products.
</P>
<P>
The organizers of the World Cup have signed an exclusive
contract with some producers who are entitled to using the logo
"France 98" and the logos.
</P>
<P>
However, officials estimate that at least from 5 to 6 percent
of the products on the World Cup now circulating around the world
are fakes.
</P>
<P>
The fake products could be sold for some 8 billion francs (1.3
billion U.S. dollars), they said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, customs officials seized 400 footballs from
Pakistan, which failed to have the flag of Japan on them due to
mistake of their producers.
</P>
<P>
Their original price was about 2 francs, but they can be sold
for 100 francs (16.7 U.S. dollars) in France. 
