<HEADLINE> Container Congestion Cripples Operation in Chittagong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's principal seaport,
Chittagong, has been again threatened with imposition of surcharge
due to constant container congestion that crippled normal
operation of the port, press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Container vessels now have to wait 7-8 days in the outer
anchorage for taking berth in the jetty and another 4-5 days for
loading and unloading at the jetty.
</P>
<P>
Foreign feeder operators have become annoyed with the present
rate of operation at the port.
</P>
<P>
The delay in the operation of container vessels is attributed
to the huge stockpile of containers in the sheds.
</P>
<P>
The holding capacity of the port is 10,5000 TEUs (tonnage
equivalent unit) of containers, but at present over 13,500 TEUs
are piled up in the container sheds for a long time, creating
accommodation problems for fresh arrivals, the reports observed.
</P>
<P>
About a year ago, the Chittagong Port Authority submitted a
proposal to the Shipping Ministry for imposition of penal rent on
containers remaining stockpiled in the sheds for more than 28
days, but no decision on the proposal was given yet.
</P>
<P>
The unusual delay of container vessels at the port has annoyed
foreign feeder operators because of increased operational cost.
</P>
<P>
The situation of the Chittagong Port, particularly the handling
of containers, has been aggravating day by day during the last two
months, the reports pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
