<HEADLINE> Hezbollah-Israel Talks on Swap Agreement Stalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Exchange of Lebanese detainees held
in Israel and the remains of an Israeli soldier will not occur
before mid-June, the Lebanese Daily Star newspaper reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A meeting between Hezbollah chief Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah and
Jean-Jacques Fresard, head of the International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC), to discuss the swap was canceled on Friday, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC has been mediating between the Lebanese resistance
force and Israel to reach a swap agreement since last September
when an Israeli commando botched a raid in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Israeli commandos were killed in the clash with Lebanese
guerrillas. The body of one of them was taken by the guerrillas.
Israel wants the return of the soldier's remains in exchange for
the release of Lebanese detainees.
</P>
<P>
"They (Israelis) said they would hand us 30 detainees but we
demanded more," Nasrallah said.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah, or Party of God, is seeking the release of 40 to
50 of its members jailed in Israel and the return of more than 40
remains, including that of Nasrallah's eldest son Hadi killed last
year.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in 1985 in south Lebanon to
allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese Muslim guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah is leading a war of attrition against the Israeli
occupation, which has resulted in heavy casualties of the Israeli
troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
