<HEADLINE> Death Toll of German Train Crash Rises to 101 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of Germany's worst
postwar railroad crash rose to 101 after rescuers found another
three bodies at the crash site near the northern German town of
Eschede, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The InterCity Express, the country's fastest train, derailed at
11:10 Wednesday morning near Eschede rail station and slammed into
a nearby road bridge, bringing hundreds of tons of concrete to
crash down onto the middle section of the train.
</P>
<P>
After three days of round-the-clock hard work, rescuers have
given up hope to find any more victims and handed over the crash
site to police investigators, who will look for possible clues
that would help to make clear how the tragedy has happened.
</P>
<P>
After initial investigations, officials said Friday that there
was an increasing belief that a broken wheel on the first coach of
the train could be the most likely cause for the derailment.
However, all other possibilities were also being investigated,
they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
