<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Hails Three-Country Oil Cut Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has said a decision made
by Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico to cut oil production would
positively affect the world oil market, Kuwait News Agency
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said the new
output reduction agreement reached by the three countries came
after a closed-door meeting, and would have a very positive effect
on the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico Thursday agreed during talks
held in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to reduce their oil production
by 450,000 barrels per day (bpd) from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Saudi Arabia will cut the output by
225,000 bpd, Venezuela by 125,000 bpd and Mexico by 100,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official expressed his country's support for any
measures that are aimed at boosting the world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
While responding to reports that Kuwait may join the efforts of
the three countries, Saud said that "any step in this regard will
only be decided after the meeting of the oil ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council due in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, on June 16."
</P>
<P>
The council, a regional political and economic alliance, groups
six Arab countries, namely Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar,
Oman and the United Arab Emirates. Their economies are heavily
reliant on oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
The world oil prices have recently slumped to 12-14 U.S.
dollars a barrel mainly due to a low demand by Southeast Asian
countries caused by the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Last March, some oil producing countries reached a deal to
slash output by 1.5 million bpd in a bid to shore up the
prices. But the move seems to have failed in attaining the goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
