<HEADLINE> ADB Offers 43 Million Dollars for Bangladesh Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has
offered a 43 million U.S. dollar investment package for
improvement of Bangladesh's two major sea ports, a major English
daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bank also suggested the privatization of the operational
activities of the Chittagong and Mengla ports to speed up cargo
handling, The Bangladesh Observer quoted Shipping Ministry sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ADB offer was made under a pre-condition that all
operational activities at the jetties and outer anchorage should
be privatized to ensure maximum service from the ports, the
sources noted.
</P>
<P>
The ADB-appointed international consultancy firm, Mott MacDonal
and Associates, had prepared a report on the Bangladesh port
upgrading project, which listed eight contract packages for the
two ports and was recently handed over to the authorities of the
two ports, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary economic analysis had also been carried out, the
sources said, adding a detailed economic and financial analysis
would be submitted with a final report to the government soon.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong port had been facing serious problems like
equipment and space shortages. 
</P>
