<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has Its First Private-Run Travel Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- China has had its first private-run
travel service, based at Shaoguan, a city in south China's
Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Cai, a former manager working for a state-owned tourism
company in Shaoguan, poured 96,000 yuan (11,000 US dollars) to win
the right to run a local travel service at a recent bidding, and
he will continue to invest 600,000 yuan in the tour agency.
</P>
<P>
Cai's case ends the situation that travel services in China are
only run by the state.
</P>
<P>
"The appearance of the private-run travel service is natural
and necessary," said Wei Xiao'an, an official of the National
Tourism Administration, in an interview today, "China encourages
the establishment of more travel services with different
ownerships, which will make the country's tourism market more
active and mature."
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that among China's top 100 domestic and 100
international travel services, Guangdong has 42 and 33,
respectively. The province also has China's first foreign-funded
hotel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
