<HEADLINE> Egypt Accuses Sudan of Harboring Mubarak's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's top security official has
said he believed Sudan was still sheltering three terrorists
charged with trying to kill President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa
in 1995, the Egyptian Gazette reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Habib el-Adli said Friday that Sudan's
failure to extradite the gunmen was blocking bilateral talks on
security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The Sudanese say the three terrorists are not in Sudan now and
that they don't know where they are," he was quoted by the
English-language daily newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We say these elements are present in Sudan and have relations
with Sudan. Things were going smoothly until Sudan refused to
extradite the terrorists... on the security level, the
negotiations stalled for that reason," he added.
</P>
<P>
El-Adli said he noticed "positive moves toward not supporting
terrorism against Egypt," during his talks here with Sudan's
Interior Minister Abdel-Raheem Mohamed Hussein in late April.
</P>
<P>
It was the first visit by Sudan's security chief to Cairo after
long months of sour ties between the two Afro-Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, along with other 30 Arab interior and justice
ministers initialed a pan Arab anti-terrorism pact.
</P>
<P>
"Sudan is not supposed to threaten Egypt's national security
because it is a brotherly nation on our borders. We urge the
Sudanese not to allow this to happen and we hope that it will not
happen," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Egypt are at odds over a border dispute and have
traded accusations of harboring militants and the oppositions, but
there are signs of a tentative thaw in relations in recent weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
