<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Greece to Sign Declaration on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Greece will sign a
declaration next week to implement the confidence-building
measures they agreed in 1988, according to the Daily News
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted diplomatic sources here as saying that the
declaration will be signed by the representatives of the two
countries in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in
Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana announced on Thursday that
Turkey and Greece, both NATO members, have informed him of their
intentions to fully implement the confidence-building measures in
order to reduce tensions between the two rival states and avoid
dangerous accidents in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece signed the Memorandum of Understanding on
May 27, 1988 in Athens, capital of Greece, and the Guidelines for
the Prevention of Accidents and Incidents on the High Seas and
International Airspaces on September 8, 1988 in Istanbul, the
largest city in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In these two agreements, both countries recognized their
obligations to respect each other's sovereignty and territorial
integrity as well as their rights to use the high seas and
international airspace of the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Tension has recently escalated between Ankara and Athens,
triggering a string of air and naval incidents in the Aegean. The
main disagreement leading to most of the incidents is the dispute
over territorial waters and airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
