<HEADLINE> Zambian Cultural Associations Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cultural Associations in Zambia
have been praised by the Zambian government for their value in
preservation and promotion of culture.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government set aside 39 million Kwacha (about
20,000 U.S. Dollars in the 1998 budget for the cultural
associations, Zambia Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Community Development and Social Services Permanent Secretary,
Helen Matanda, said in Kwbwe, central Zambia, on Friday that
cultural administrators need to be equipped with skills to
effectively conduct research and advise the government on changes
deemed necessary, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closure of a research skills training course
for provincial cultural officers, Matanda said that the course is
part of the Community Development Ministry's capacity building
program.
</P>
<P>
The cause aims to improve operations and enhance effectiveness and
efficiency in the service, said the official.
</P>
<P>
"Technological development has made global communication so
easy that we can literally exchange information with any part of
the world at the touch of a button. These developments have had
an impact on our society," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Our culture has been globally acknowledged as the basis for
sustainable development and that cultural dimensions of human
life are very essential," she said.
</P>
<P>
Matanda noted that development and economy are part of
people's culture and if development is divorced from its human or
cultural content, it becomes meaningless.
</P>
<P>
She said it is necessary for everybody to appreciate the
cultural values of each community to ensure that development
strategies meet cultural requirements of the people.
</P>
<P>
She urged officers to carry out their duties more effectively
because of the knowledge they have acquired.
</P>
<P>
She promised to supply them with equipment for them to carry
out their work effectively.
</P>
<P>
"This year, we have an allocation for the procurement of
cultural research equipment and these will be made available to
you soon," Matanda said.  
</P>
