<HEADLINE> Talks Between Striking Pilots, Management Break Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The talks between the striking pilots
of Air France and the company's management broke down early
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
If the talks can resume on Monday as the earliest, time is
running out for preparing for the opening day of the Football
World Cup finals in the country on June 10, as the preparation
time for pilots to fly planes needs 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
President and Chief Executive Officer of Air France Jean-Cyril
Spinetta said that the pilots should take realistic measures to go
out of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The biggest union of pilots, the SNPL, stepped out of the talks
Saturday morning, a few hours after Spinetta himself left the
negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
Only 25 percent of the short, medium- and long-haul planes of
Air France are expected to take off Saturday, Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pilots went on strike on June 1 because the air company
planned to reduce their salaries by 15 percent in exchange for its
shares. The strikers also wanted the scrapping of a double system
in pays between older and younger pilots. 
</P>
