<HEADLINE> Somali Gunmen Kidnap French Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Two French nationals and their
small boat were kidnaped Friday by Somali gunmen off the coast of
the Northeastern town of Bossaso.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the boat of the French men
had been intercepted by another speed boat of Somali gunmen close
to the junction of the Red Sea and the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The French men told their abductors that they are tourists who
sailed from the port of Marseille of France through the Canal
Suez and that they were heading towards the island of Madagasar.
</P>
<P>
The French men had a gun with them on the boat. The tourists
told their abductors that they had their gun for merely hunting
purposes.
</P>
<P>
According to the Somali gunmen loyal to the Somali Salvation
Democratic Front (SSDF) who are popular in their sea pirates
operations, the French men had trespassed into their exclusive
economic zone of the sea, getting as close as only three
kilometers to where Somali fishermen were conducting their
fishing business.
</P>
<P>
One of the security officers of SSDF, Said Dhere, told the
journalists that the French men's case will be subjected to a
serious investigation before making any kind of a decision.
</P>
<P>
The head of the gunmen who abducted the French men, Saeed
Bani'adam, said there will be no other way out, but huge ransom
to be paid in an exchange for the release of the French men. He
did not disclose how much money they will ask for.
</P>
<P>
The Northeastern SSDF gunmen who are equipped with speed boats
and assault rifles and heavy machine guns, patrol beyond their
limit in the Red Sea and Indian Ocean for hunting foreign vessels
as their best revenue making business.
</P>
<P>
Each vessel caught is charged with money between 200,000 U.S.
Dollars and 500,000 U.S. Dollars, according to status and
economical standard of the prey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
