<HEADLINE> North China Province Uses Foreign Funds for Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
has launched 11 pollution control projects with foreign funds of
nearly 200 million US dollars since 1990, according to sources
from the provincial environmental protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
The Baiyangdian Lake, the largest in north China which covers
366 sq km, is one of the major beneficiaries of such projects.
</P>
<P>
To protect the lake, Hebei provincial government used a
low-interest loan of 6.7 million US dollars from the government of
Finland, in addition to the Chinese government investment, to set
up two sewage treatment plants in Baoding City near the lake.
</P>
<P>
The province also used 13 million Deutsche Marks (7.3 million
US dollars) from the German government to build ecological forests
along the upper reaches of the Baiyangdian Lake.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the province has used 55 million US dollars from the
Asian Development Bank to curb pollution produced by coal-burning
in winter, and utilized loans from other countries to treat
polluted water in some of the province's major cities such as
Shijiazhuang, the provincial capital, and Handan.
</P>
<P>
The province's enterprises have also joined the efforts to
introduce foreign funds for pollution control, the sources said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
