<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Urges Ethiopia, Eritrea to End Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- African ministers of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) urgently appealed to
Ethiopia and Eritrea here Saturday morning to put an end to all
hostilities for a peaceful solution to their border dispute.
</P>
<P>
In a special session which ended at midnight Friday, the OAU
Council of Ministers urged the two parties to do so "at the same
and simultaneously", Salim Ahmed Salim, Secretary-General of OAU
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The special session, the second in two days during the 68th
ordinary session of the OAU Council of Ministers starting here
Thursday morning, followed the mutual air bombing Friday by the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia said Friday afternoon that Eritrea air bombed its
northern border town of Mekelle, wounding five civilians, while
Eritrea claimed to be bombed by four Ethiopian fighter planes in
two rounds of attacks against the southern outskirts of its
capital Asmara.
</P>
<P>
The escalation of hostilities followed an urgent session
called by the ministerial council and the Central Organ of the
OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution
Thursday night, when both parties were urged to exercise
restraint to enable a peaceful settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to Salim, the session on Friday night heard the
report of the facilitators on the evolution of the situation
between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two countries also briefed the session,
said Salim.
</P>
<P>
"The spirit of response given by the two parties has been
positive to the appeal by the council," he added.
</P>
<P>
As the appeal represents the collective concern of Africa, the
OAU chief hoped the two parties will pay heed to it.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the gravity of the situation and the loss of
lives," the Council of Ministers meeting "recommends to the heads
of state and government to be immediately seized with the
matter," according to the resolution adopted by the session.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of OAU members states will begin to arrive at the
capital of Burkina Faso to attend the 34th summit of the
continental organization which is to open next Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
