<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shortsightedness Plagues Half of Chinese Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Shortsightedness arising from
excessively heavy load of study and lack of care for eyes are
plaguing more and more Chinese adolescents, ophthalmologists
warned.
</P>
<P>
On average, more than half of students across the country have
suffered from myopia, or shortsightedness, in different degrees,
according to a national investigation of students' physical and
health situations.
</P>
<P>
The incidence was about 23 percent in primary schools, 55
percent in junior middle schools, 70 percent in high schools and
77 percent in colleges and universities, said the survey which was
jointly conducted by ministries of Health and Education.
</P>
<P>
The survey result also showed that the incidence in cities was
much higher than that in rural areas, while girls are more
vulnerable to the disease than boys.
</P>
<P>
Long-period tiredness of eyes dominated the causes of
nearsightedness, apart from some hereditary factors, said Dr. Xu
Liang, director of the Beijing Ophthalmological Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
He warned of a rise of the incidence if young people continue
to underestimate the harmfulness of overuse of eyes.
</P>
<P>
However, primary and middle school students have to stick their
eyes to books and blackboards for some eight to ten hours a day,
compared with only one to two hours for them to have a rest,
according to a survey conducted in 93 schools in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Ignorance of prevention and control of overuse of eyes may
lead to not only shortsightedness, but even blindness," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Out of four to five million blind people in China, some 300,000
were victims of serious shortsightedness.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, there is one amblyopia patient among every 30
Chinese children, whose sight defects will not be corrected if
they can not get prompt diagnosis and treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health has designated the sixth day of June as
the National Eye Care Day in a bid to raise awareness of the
public to protect their eyes and help them to increase knowledge
in this field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
