<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Stand on Border Demarcation Dangerous: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has said a recent
Iraqi statement over the U.N. border demarcation between the two
countries was a dangerous step that reflects Iraq's true
intention toward Kuwait, Kuwait News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A Kuwaiti foreign ministry spokesman said on Friday that Kuwait
would take a legal and political action through the Arab League
and the U.N. Security Council in a bid to preserve its rights and
enforce the full implementation of the U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan has reportedly said in
Rabat, Morocco, where he was on a visit, that the U.N. border
demarcation resolution has no legal value.
</P>
<P>
In May 1993, the U.N. Security Council adopted resolution 833,
which delimits the boundary between Kuwait and Iraq. In November
1994, Iraq announced to recognize the boundary.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's recognition of the border between the two countries is
one of the main demands it should meet in relevant resolutions
passed by the U.N. Security Council after Iraq was defeated in the
1991 Gulf War touched off by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti spokesman said Ramadan's statement was a very
dangerous position revealing the true intention of the Iraqi
policy toward Kuwait and international agreements.
</P>
<P>
Rebuffing the statement, the spokesman said the U.N. resolution
has been endorsed by Iraq's National Assembly (parliament),
Revolutionary Command Council and government.
</P>
<P>
This has been officially documented at the United Nations, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
