<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir: Economic Recovery in Malaysia Takes Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Saturday that his country will take some
time to recover from the current economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
The resilience and sacrifices of the people are needed to face
the situation, Mahathir said. "While we do not reject the role of
outsiders in helping us to deal with the situation, we cannot
totally depend on them."
</P>
<P>
"Recovery will not come easy but we are confident that by
reducing the country's dependence on foreign exchange, we will
somewhat escape the threats of attacks on our currency and the
nation's economy," he said in a speech at the investiture in
conjunction with the birthday of Malaysia's Supreme Head of State
Tuanku Ja'afar here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said various efforts and strategies had been taken by the
government to reduce the impact of the devalued ringgit, including
cutting down on imports and less consumption of essential items
like sugar, flour and milk, encouraging prudent spending,
promoting exports and ensuring that in its trade with other
countries, the ringgit or the currency of the other trading
country was used, and several other measures to revive the
nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government was confident that Malaysia would
be able to overcome the economic problems it was facing based on
the nation's political and social stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that the people's faith and confidence in the
government was most vital because not all the government's
approaches could be publicly announced.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir pledged that the government would take heed of all the
problems faced by the people and provide assistance to all parties
such as the retrenched workers, traders and small or big
entrepreneurs so that they will not face too much pressure as a
result of factors beyond their control.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir expressed gratitude for the fact that the country had
remained peaceful with the people living in harmony in the wake of
the economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
