<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Not to Devalue Dong: Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister and
Governor of the State Bank of Vietnam Nguyen Tan Dung said that
his country would not devalued its currency "dong", the English
newspaper "Vietnam News" reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's economic and political conditions do not allow
devaluation and floating of the dong, Dung said.
</P>
<P>
The immediate banking priority was to control the monetary and
credit policies aimed at stabilizing the macro economy and
maintaining economic growth in an unexpected, difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties include the continued influence of the
monetary and financial crisis in Asia, and the long drought which
has caused a loss of estimated 400 million U.S. dollars, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Dung said that banking activities must be aimed at increasing
the capacity to pay, keeping inflation at a single digit and
taking reasonable measures to maintain the value of dong.
</P>
<P>
However, the deputy prime minister also told a media conference
here on Friday that the Vietnamese government would continue to
take flexible and careful steps to regulate exchange rate in
accordance with the conditions of supply and demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
