<HEADLINE> Canada's Province to Compensate Sterilization Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian province of Alberta
said Friday that it will compensate some 500 people who were
sterilized without their permission before 1972.
</P>
<P>
The settlement will cost the province 33 million U.S. dollars,
or about 69,000 dollars per person, said reports from the province.
</P>
<P>
Most of those included in the package remain in provincial
care, and the deal was struck between Alberta's Justice Department
and a provincially appointed trustee.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the settlement is fair and achieves a reasonable
balance between the interests of the individuals and the interests
of Albertans," Justice Minister Jon Havelock said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 250 to 300 victim claims not covered by Friday's
agreement will be settled on the same basis, Havelock added.
</P>
<P>
Between 1928 and 1972, more than 2,000 Albertans were
sterilized under the province's sterilization act, which was
designed to prevent the mentally handicapped from passing on their
genes to offspring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
