<HEADLINE> OAU Urges Ethiopia, Eritrea to End Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- African ministers have urgently
appealed to Ethiopia and Eritrea to end all hostilities and to
work for a peaceful solution to their border dispute.
</P>
<P>
In a special session which ended at midnight Friday, the OAU
Council of Ministers urged the two countries to end the conflict
simultaneously, Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) said Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The special session, the second in two days during the 68th
ordinary session of the OAU Council of Ministers, was held after
the air raids Friday by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia said Friday afternoon that Eritrea bombed its northern
border town of Mekelle, wounding five civilians, while Eritrea
claimed four Ethiopian fighter planes attacked twice on the
southern outskirts of the capital Asmara.
</P>
<P>
The escalation of hostilities followed an urgent session called
by the Council and the Central Organ of the OAU Mechanism for
Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution Thursday night,
when restraint was urged to enable a peaceful settlement of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to Salim, the session on Friday night heard a report
on the unfolding conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
"The spirit of response given by the two parties has been
positive to the appeal by the Council," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
As the appeal represents the collective concern of Africa, the
OAU chief hoped the two parties would pay heed to it.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of OAU members states will begin to arrive at the
capital of Burkina Faso to attend the 34th summit which is to open
next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
