<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Set New Rules for Foreigner Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will soon
complete a new draft of the foreign business law which is expected
to stimulate more capital inflow.
</P>
<P>
A committee reviewing the regulation of foreign business in
Thailand has reached agreement that a working group be set up to
outline what investments would be opened for foreigners, Deputy
Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said in remarks published by
today's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
The working group will have one month to finish the draft
before submitting it to parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
If the bill is enacted into law, it will replace the Alien
Business Law, which the past four governments had pledged to amend
but later had the process sidelined.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said the new law would allow a wider range of
investment for foreigners, except in businesses concerning
national security, the economy and culture which would be reserved
for Thais only.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would also have more flexibility to
change the lists of reserved occupations at any time.
</P>
<P>
Critical conditions that would benefit Thailand, such as volume
of investment, methods of bringing in capital from abroad and the
number of foreigners to be employed, would be stated in the draft,
Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
He said other related laws including the Insurance Law,
Condominium Act for Foreign Ownership and the Land Law would be
amended simultaneously to allow foreign investors greater
participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
