<HEADLINE> 9 International Banks Named to Back Up Indonesia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
appointed nine international investment banks to assist in the
partial privatization of 12 state companies, press reports
Saturday quoted a government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached after a vigorous and thorough
selection process which involved 22 international banks, said
State Minister for the Empowerment of State Enterprises Tanri
Abeng here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said the selection criteria were designed together with the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government plans to privatize seven state-owned
companies and divest more shares in five publicly listed state
companies in the 1998-99 fiscal year ending March 31, 1999 in a
bid to raise 15 trillion rupiah (about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars)
to support the financially strained state budget.
</P>
<P>
Abeng said the government hopes that the program will help
restore confidence in the country's economy and improve the
competitiveness of state companies.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said the government is willing to lower its
requirement of a 51 percent stake in state companies.
</P>
<P>
"When investors are injecting millions of dollars, or maybe
billions of dollars, they want to have a say in management. We
have to be realistic," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government aims to privatize telecommunications
firm Telkom, international telecommunications carrier Indosat,
cement-making, steel-making and mining companies, and toll road,
airport, plantation and port management companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
