<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai Releases First Environmental Protection Bulletin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Province in northwest China
has recently released its first bulletin on the province's
environmental situation in the year 1997, claiming it has obtained
fruitful results in the field.
</P>
<P>
Remarkable progress has been made in the fields of prevention
and treatment of industrial pollution, ecological environment
building, and adoption of regulations and laws on environmental
protection, said Kang Weixin, director of the Provincial
Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Located in northeast of the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau, the
province has a fragile ecological environment with serious land
erosion, desertification, and grassland degradation problems.
</P>
<P>
The province has launched several large-scale comprehensive
pollution treatment projects for the plateau environment in recent
years. It has set up four nature reserves and two state-level
forest parks, among which, the Qinghaihu Lake and Longbaotan
nature reserves have already been listed as the world's important
wetlands. The number of birds inhabiting the Qinghaihu Lake has
been restored to the record level of 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin shows that the province last year treated eroded
land area of 544,000 hectares; afforesting 35,600 hectares of
land; and improving grassland area of 278,500 hectares. The
province has also made remarkable progress in the comprehensive
treatment of waste gas, waste water, and industrial residue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980606.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most College Graduates Find Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 80 percent of the bachelors
who are expected to graduate from Chinese universities this year
have found jobs, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an Education Ministry official as saying that
"graduate students are the most popular in the job
market". However, they have to face a more market-oriented
employment situation and there is pressure, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The graduates' problems stem from the restructuring of the
government earlier this year, the increase in the number of the
workers laid off by state-owned enterprises and the huge number of
graduates, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
China this year saw the largest number of college graduates
since the founding of the People's Republic in 1949.
</P>
<P>
College students had had no problems in finding jobs until the
early 1990s when China started to change the practice of job
assignment for graduates.
</P>
<P>
To help students who have not found a job, the State Council
has published a circular calling on employers at all levels to
help them and not to neglect them, the paper adds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
