<HEADLINE> Beijing's Four-Month Exports up 26.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital reported
continued hefty export growth in the first four months of this
year despite the Southeast Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's overall foreign trade volume surged 10.5 percent on a
yearly basis to 1.846 billion US dollars for the January-April
period, with exports surging 26.8 percent to 897 million US
dollars and imports dropping 14 percent to 949 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The capital's export growth rate is 15 percentage points higher
than the national figure during the same period.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that exports by state-owned enterprises
reached 490 million US dollars in the first four months, up 28
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, Beijing's general trade exports rose 13
percent year-on-year to 380 million US dollars for the
January-April period, while exports of processed goods surged 28
percent to 460 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though exports to Southeast Asian countries, Japan and the
Republic of Korea declined, Beijing's exports to other countries
and regions continued to increase in the first four months.
</P>
<P>
To be specific, exports to Europe rocketed 83 percent to 240
million US dollars. Exports to the United States rose 38 percent
to 110 million US dollars while those to Africa doubled to 23.82
million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
