<HEADLINE> Costa Rican President to Attend U.N. Drug Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican President Miguel Angel
Rodriguez will demand at the U.N. that the world's wealthier
countries do more in the battle against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez, accompanied by Foreign Minister Roberto Rojas and
Commerce Minister Samuel Guzowski, left for the United States on
Friday to attend the U.N. General Assembly special session on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica would ask drug-consuming nations to increase their
efforts against the production, transportation and consumption of
drugs, Rojas said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The position we are taking to New York is that the
countries that consume drugs should also take part in all the
efforts. It is not fair to blame only the producers, which are
poor countries."
</P>
<P>
Representatives of about 150 countries, including 35 heads of
state and government, are to attend the three-day conference which
opens on Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials said the conference will focus on issues such as
ways to combat money-laundering, reducing demand, strengthening
judicial cooperation, regulating chemicals used to synthesize
drugs and eliminating the illegal cultivation of poppy, coca and
cannabis crops.
</P>
<P>
During his seven-day trip to the United States, Rodriguez will
meet U.S. politicians such as former President Jimmy Carter and
Senator Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet representatives of the 90 most important
companies with investments in Latin America. "The idea is to
promote the country during the meeting, they are going to be told
they are welcome," Rojas explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
