<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government Reacts to P-5 Joint Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government in a
statement Friday evening criticized the communique issued by
foreign ministers of the five permanent Security Council member
countries (P-5) Thursday over the tense situation in the South
Asian region following the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In their one-day meeting in Geneva, the P-5 asked India and
Pakistan to have direct dialogue to reduce tension, refrain from
weaponization or deployment of nuclear weapons and adhere to the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) immediately and
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the Kashmir issue, the root cause of
tension between India and Pakistan and urged the two countries to
make efforts to resolve disputes including Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
India in its statement Friday rejected outright any third party
mediation on Kashmir issue. "We reiterate once again that there is
no room for any outside involvement of any nature whatsoever in
this process," the statement said in response to the P-5
communique.
</P>
<P>
The P-5 communique said that India and Pakistan do not have the
status of nuclear weapon state in accordance with the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), notwithstanding their recent
nuclear tests. India in its Friday statement regards itself as "a
nuclear weapon state".
</P>
<P>
The Indian government statement also criticized the nuclear
weapon states for not taking "credible and effective steps" to
establish a comprehensive and equitable regime of nuclear
disarmament in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
