<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 5 (xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy today deplored the mounting conflict between
Ethiopia and Eritrea, and urged both sides to resolve their
dispute peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"Canada hopes that there will be a peaceful resolution of the
border issue without further bloodshed," said Axworthy. He called
on both sides to refrain from further fighting and to cooperate
with mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Canadian concerns about mounting tensions were earlier conveyed
to the Ethiopian and Eritrean authorities by the Department of
Foreign Affairs and International Trade (DFAIT) in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
The DFAIT issued a travel advisory today advising Canadians to
defer travel to Eritrea or, if in the country, to depart
immediately. There are approximately 125 Canadians in Eritrea
registered with the Canadian Embassy in Addis Ababa and the
Consulate in Asmara, the Eritrean capital.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has escalated with bombing attacks Friday on Makele in
Ethiopia and on Asmara. The current fighting between the two
countries was precipitated by a border skirmish on May 6. 
