<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beaten to Rank 12th at Women's Basketball Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China lost their last game to
Germany 60-90 on Friday to finish 12th, the lowest ranking since
they made a debut at the world basketball championship in 1983
when they came fifth.
</P>
<P>
China, which won a silver medal in the 1992 Barcelona Olympic
Games, finished second in last world championship in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side came from 8-13 and 12-15 down to tie the game
15-all and take over 25-24 on Miao Bo's jumper with 7:54 to play in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, Miao injured her right foot when she jumped for
a shot and was forced to the bench. Giant center Zheng Haixia was
also benched there.
</P>
<P>
The Germans made a 14-2 run to put themselves 38-27 up and
walked off court with a 42-33 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
Center Heike Roth led Germany with 20 points and her teammate
Marilies Askamp added 19. Ma Chengqing scored 16 points and
grabbed 13 rebounds, followed by Zheng Haixia's 15 points in her
25 minutes play.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Ma Yuenan told a post-game news conference that
his team didn't play their game. "They lost their hearts for
victory," said the 37-year-old coach.
</P>
<P>
"Such a disappointing game, such a disappointing
championship. We had never had worse placing," said five-time
world championship veteran Zheng Haixia.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old Haixia will leave for the United States on
Monday to take part in the training camp of the WNBA's
Sparkers. This will be her second season in the WNBA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
