<HEADLINE> China Trade Fair Opens in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A trade show attended by Chinese
exporters opened here Friday at the Javits Convention Center, the
largest show room of New York.
</P>
<P>
A total of 145 exhibitors, mainly from Hangzhou, capital city
of eastern China's Zhejiang Province, displayed a big variety of
goods, ranging from foodstuffs to toys, garments and other light
industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou, the famous scenic city of the country, has speeded up
its process of opening to the outside world, while greatly
improving its investment facilities, according to Chen Rufang,
director of the city's Foreign Economic Relations and Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou has become a home for 403 U.S. companies, who invested
a total of 904 million U.S. dollars. Their businesses cover a wide
range of industries, including electronics, telecommunication,
tourism, energy, auto parts, pharmaceutical and chemical items,
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Also joining the show were a number of land developers from
Shanghai. They offer sites for building a luxurious new
residential quarter near the city's international airport and for
setting up firms in a major free trade zone at Waigaoqiao in the
Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Gansu Province in western China is also holding a trade fair in
the downtown area in New York. The Gansu delegation has brought
over 36 major construction projects to lure investors. Most of the
projects are located in Lanzhou, the provincial capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
