<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Hits Another 7-Year High Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar reached yet
another seven-year high against the Japanese yen Friday as traders
believed in a stronger U.S. economy as indicated by a low
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was higher against the German mark and other
major currencies, but the Friday market primarily centered on
dollar-yen trading.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 139.75 yen,
up from 138.27 yen late Thursday. Earlier, the dollar rose as high
as 139.93 yen, a mark not seen since June 20, 1991.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.7745 marks in New York,
up from 1.7654 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar edged toward the 140-yen level, boosted by a Labor
Department report showing that the U.S. unemployment rate remained
at 4.3 percent in May, a 28-year low.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.4765 Swiss francs, up from 1.4688; 5.9500 French
francs, up from 5.9175; 1,747.00 Italian lire, up from 1,746.84;
and 1.4577 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4543.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6353 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6369 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
