<HEADLINE> 1998 U.N. Population Award Winners Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sabiny Elders
Association of Uganda which curtailed female genital mutilation in
Uganda and Jamaican Hugh H. Wynter are winners of the 1998 U.N.
Population Award, it was announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Award Committee said that the association has reduced
female genital mutilation by 36 percent in the Sabiny Community in
Northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wynter, chairman of Jamaica's national Family Planning
Board, was nominated for his work in promoting safe and effective
family planning.
</P>
<P>
He trained scores of medical doctors and is generally credited
as one of the most important people in helping his country to
achieve one of the lowest rates of population growth, fertility
and infant mortality in the region.
</P>
<P>
He has also assisted many other Caribbean countries with their
national family planning programs.
</P>
<P>
The 25,000 U.S. dollar award is presented annually to
individuals and institutions which have made outstanding
contributions to increasing the awareness of population problems
and to their solutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
