<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two More Victims in German Rail Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Another two people injured in
Germany's worst post-war railroad crash two days ago died in
hospitals Friday evening, bringing the latest death toll to 98,
German officials said.
</P>
<P>
The InterCity Express (ICE), the country's fastest train,
derailed at 11:10 Wednesday morning near the northern German town
of Eschede and slammed into a nearby road bridge, bringing
hundreds of tons of concrete to crash down onto the middle section
of the train.
</P>
<P>
So far, 94 bodies have been recovered from the wreckage and a
nearby slope so far. Another two people died of injuries Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
After two days of intensive work, rescuers have cleared all
crashed train carriages from the debris. At the moment they are
still trying to lift huge chunks of the collapsed bridge in a last
attempt to find out whether there are any more victims under the
debris.
</P>
<P>
Officials expected the rescue operations to be completed late
in the evening so that investigators could make a thorough checkup
of the crash site Saturday to look for possible clues that would
help to make clear how the crash happened.
</P>
<P>
After initial investigations, officials said Friday that a
broken wheel on the first coach of the train could be the most
likely cause for the derailment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
