<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Ready to Work With UNSCOM: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is ready to work with
U.N. arms inspectors and the Security Council on the question of
its disarmament, Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahaf said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, he told a press conference, such a working manner
should be based on a "professional, technical and scientific
approach."
</P>
<P>
He termed the latest conditions for the arms inspection in Iraq
put forward by the UNSCOM, the U.N. Special Commission in charge
of scrapping Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, as "politically
motivated" instead of a "road map" described by UNSCOM head
Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who goes to Baghdad next week to talk with Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tareq Aziz on what Iraq should do to show it has
met the requirements under the relevant U.N. resolution, briefed
the Security Council on the UNSCOM's views this week.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Thursday, Butler declined to elaborate
the contents, but said they cover the main priority issues
including prohibited missiles, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq has been far less revealing to us over the years with
respect to its biological program than it has with respect to
chemical or missiles" programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also declined to speculate about actual figures, explaining
that it was "up to Iraq to tell us what the real numbers are -- we
match that with the information we have."
</P>
<P>
Butler said that if Iraq will provide all information and
materials the UNSCOM needs, his report to the Security Council in
October will be "very different" from the previous ones.
</P>
<P>
Sahaf, who came here nine days ago to argue for the lifting of
U.N. sanctions against Iraq, said the UNSCOM' requirements are
"nothing new" but "more vague than what it was before" with an
aim to "complicate the situation."
</P>
<P>
Sahaf said Iraq has implemented all requirements under the
U.N. resolution, urging that sanctions be lifted immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Hundreds of thousands of Iraqis have died because of the most
severe and inhumane sanctions" in the past seven years, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
