<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Deadbeat Parents Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Friday passed a
bill which makes it a federal felony for parents to cross state
lines to evade child support.
</P>
<P>
It would apply if the amount owed is 5,000 dollars or more and
the payments are more than one year delinquent.
</P>
<P>
It would also apply if the child lives in a different state
than the parent responsible for the payments, and the parent
"willfully" fails to make the payments.
</P>
<P>
The Deadbeat Parents Act of 1998, sponsored by Representatives
Henry Hyde, a Republican, and Steny Hoyer, a Democrat, will be
signed by President Bill Clinton, according to aides for both
authors.
</P>
<P>
The Senate, which approved a similar bill last year, passed it
by voice vote, without debate. The House overwhelmingly approved
it last month.
</P>
<P>
Parents owing 10,000 dollars or more or those fail to pay for
two years could face up to two years in prison. Parents could also
face fines and would be responsible for making restitution for
unpaid child support.
</P>
<P>
Hoyer said the bill would help close loopholes in the system
which allow parents to slip across state lines to avoid paying
child support, thus leaving children and families in economic
ruins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
