<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves GOP Plan to Cut Spending, Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Friday approved a Republican plan to cut domestic
spending by an additional 101 billion dollars through 2003 and
slice taxes by the same amount.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers voted 216-204 to approve a 1.72 trillion dollar
budget for 1999 containing the reductions. By an early unofficial
count, all but nine Republicans ended up supporting the plan.
</P>
<P>
The vote was held after a frantic, eleventh-hour debate and
bargaining between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Before the vote, Republican leaders requested unhappy moderates
to support the package because a more modest plan would inevitably
emerge from negotiations with the more centrist Senate. The
leaders also argued that the cuts were just 1 percent of the 9
trillion dollars the government plans to spend over the next five
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
