<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Bounces Back to 9,000 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks shot higher Friday
as a robust job report helped calm concerns about company profits.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 167.15 points to
9,037.71, the biggest gain in four months and the first close
above 9,000 in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market indicators also posted big gains, although
the Nasdaq composite index rose only modestly.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 19.03 to 1,113.86, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 12.97 to 1,782.92.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled 556.50
million shares as against 568.96 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 9.02, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index rose 3.66 to 713.12.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.61 to
453.36.
</P>
<P>
The rally began after the Labor Department reported that the
nation's unemployment rate held at a 28-year low of 4.3 percent in
May. The rate matched April's reading, which was the lowest since
February 1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
